          "body": "With the sovereign oracle still ringing in the air, David asks the most haunting question in the psalm: 'Who will bring me into the besieged city? Who will lead me to Edom?' (v. 10). God just said Edom is His. Yet David cannot reach it. The gap between verse 9 and verse 10 is the psalm's central pastoral space — the space where believers who know the promises live. Verse 11 names it without flinching: 'Have not You Yourself, O God, rejected us? And will You not go forth with our armies, O God?' This is not apostasy; it is the covenant cry of a community that takes God's promise seriously enough to notice when the experience contradicts it. Jonathan Edwards in *Charity and Its Fruits* observed that genuine faith is proved not by the absence of such cries but by the direction in which the cry is aimed — at God, not away from Him. David's lament is addressed directly to God, twice naming Him 'O God.' The lament is itself an act of covenant loyalty."
