          "title": "The resolution — through God, not by man (vv. 12-13)",
          "body": "The psalm resolves not by suppressing the lament but by redirecting it. Verse 12 names the epistemological turning point: 'deliverance by man is in vain.' This is not general pessimism about human effort — it is the covenant community's recognition that the besieged city (v. 10) and the entrenched enemy (Edom, v. 10) lie beyond human capacity, that the oracle of verses 7-9 will be fulfilled by the One who spoke it, not by the armies that hear it. The response to 'help by man is vain' is therefore not passivity but re-grounded action: 'Through God we will do valiantly, and it is He who shall tread down our adversaries' (v. 13). The grammar is precise — the valor is Israel's ('we will do valiantly'), but the agency is God's ('it is He who shall tread down'). Douglas Moo's principle of divine-human agency, developed in his treatment of Romans 8:37, applies here: the believer is 'more than a conqueror through Him who loved us' — through Him, not independently. The psalm's final word is not the enemy's defeat but God's trampling. Israel fights; God treads them down."
